english:
  title: The Discourse on the Snow Ox
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Venerable One called Milk-Giver is a disciple of Bodhisattva Samantabhadra. He participated in the printing of the Great Canon and in its recitation as well. With a countenance pure and conduct complete, he stands foremost among his peers. Thus Bodhisattva Samantabhadra named him the Snow Ox—and there is reason in this.

    Let me expound upon this meaning: Snow refers to the Snowy Mountains, and Ox to the cattle that graze there. The virtues of their milk are detailed in the Buddhist scriptures, which lie beyond my knowing. Yet milk itself is the nourishment that both man and beast give to what they have brought forth. Once form is born, without milk there is no sustenance. Thus milk enables the proper functioning of nature and destiny itself. The beneficence of milk is vast. That Bodhisattva Samantabhadra alone chose this name befits his teaching, which takes purity and clarity as its root and transformation as its function.

    The Snowy Mountains are the lofty and crystalline heights of the Western regions, where fragrant grasses flourish abundantly. The oxen that graze within such terrain grow robust and sleek; their very dung, pure as it is, serves in the preparation of sacred ground. Thus the body becomes undefiled and uncorrupted, the vital essence remains whole and undegraded. The dharma hall stands austere and sanctified, precepts refined with utmost care. Through this, great compassion is awakened and ancient defilements are washed away. One may then enter the gate of meditative absorption.

    It is true that in the Chan and scriptural teachings, oxen are understood in four ways, and also in ten ways. These interpretations differ from one another and need not be debated. The Snow Ox turns its body, gazing westward. Thus I speak these words for the Venerable One: When shall your dharma milk, like nourishment itself, pervade all sentient beings? Strive ever more diligently toward this.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Bodhisattva Samantabhadra (普濟) is referenced here as the master who bestowed the name 'Snow Ox.' In Chinese Buddhist tradition, this refers to the bodhisattva associated with universal compassion and practice.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Snowy Mountains' (設山) represent the sacred geography of Buddhist cosmology, often associated with spiritual purity and the source of dharma.
  - key: ''
    value: The dharma milk (法乳) is a classical Buddhist metaphor for the transmission of Buddhist teaching, suggesting nourishment for spiritual growth.
  - key: ''
    value: '''All sentient beings'' (含識) refers to all creatures possessing consciousness, central to Buddhist concepts of compassion and salvation.'
